{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:56:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:56:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12832"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12832"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.43,0.07,0.01,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77306"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5275"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62813"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44795"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77306"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a 4-week history of a dry cough, worsening shortness of breath, and feeling generally fatigued. On further questioning, he reveals a 5kg unintentional weight loss in the last three months but denies haemoptysis and fever. He has no sick contacts. His history is relevant for diet-controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His regular medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. He reports a 50-pack-year history of smoking and minimal alcohol consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe physical examination is unremarkable. A chest X-ray shows an 8mm nodule in the right upper lobe of the lung and right-sided costophrenic angle blunting.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchoscopy \u00b1 biopsy of nodule","CT-chest","PET-CT","Repeat chest X-ray in six weeks","Diagnostic pleural fluid aspiration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical picture is suggestive of lung cancer. This is supported by the radiological findings of a pulmonary nodule and pleural effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step would be a\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003Echest CT with IV contrast.\u003C/strong\u003E The current guidelines recommend a\u00a0CT chest if there is a strong clinical suspicion of lung cancer, persistent or unexplained haemoptysis, signs of superior vena cava obstruction or imaging findings suggest lung cancer (as in this case) within two weeks of the patient presenting with symptoms. Following the scan, the patient should then be referred to a specialist for consideration of further investigation and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003Emay be able to provide a definitive diagnosis of lung cancer and its classification when accompanied by a biopsy of the nodule. This is an invasive procedure that would be performed after further investigation by a chest CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic pleural fluid aspiration\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003Emay have diagnostic and therapeutic benefits in this case, however, according to the imaging pathway guidelines is not indicated before a CT scan of the chest. If performed, it may provide symptomatic relief of dyspnoea, and an aspirate may be sent for cytology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA PET scan \u003C/strong\u003Emay be used in the staging process for lung cancer but it is not the first choice for further investigation of a suspicious lung nodule with a history suggestive of lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat chest X-ray in six weeks.\u003C/strong\u003E A repeat chest X-ray may be indicated in a patient with persistent symptoms, despite no suggestive findings of respiratory disease on the initial X-ray, which is not the case for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A chest CT scan should be performed if there is a strong clinical suspicion of lung cancer"],"references":["Thomas K, Gould M, Naeger D. Overview of the initial evaluation, diagnosis, and staging of patients with suspected lung cancer. UpToDate. Updated April 2023. Accessed May, 2023. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-the-initial-evaluation-diagnosis-and-staging-of-patients-with-suspected-lung-cancer?search=lung%20cancer%20diagnosis\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1","McLellan R, et al. Diagnosis and treatment of early lung cancer. Australian Journal of General Practice. Updated August, 2020. Accessed May, 2023. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-11-19-5148","Mazzone PJ, Silvestri GA, Patel S, Kanne JP, Kinsinger LS, Wiener RS, Soo Hoo G, Detterbeck FC. Screening for Lung Cancer: CHEST Guideline and Expert Panel Report. Chest. 2018 Apr;153(4):954-985. doi: 10.1016/j.chest.2018.01.016. Epub 2018 Feb 17. PMID: 29374513.","Silvestri GA, Goldman L, Tanner NT, Burleson J, Gould M, Kazerooni EA, Mazzone PJ, Rivera MP, Doria-Rose VP, Rosenthal LS, Simanowith M, Smith RA, Fedewa S. Outcomes From More Than 1 Million People Screened for Lung Cancer With Low-Dose CT Imaging. Chest. 2023 Jul;164(1):241-251. doi: 10.1016/j.chest.2023.02.003. Epub 2023 Feb 10. PMID: 36773935; PMCID: PMC10331628."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62813"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12832"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62813"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:47:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:47:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5275"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77306"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.e